<h2><i class="mch-book-open"></i> 2.2.1 PROFICIENCY</h2>
<div class="evidenceBorder">
  <h3><i class="mch-search"></i> <img src="../../images/smart-1-1-magnifying-glass.jpg" alt="Image of Magnifying Glass" class="right ppic" />REVIEW. The Competency in Detail</h3>
  <p>The following drop-downs contain information on each of the knowledge areas and skills needed to implement the competency. <strong>Please explore the content below.</strong></p>
  <h3>Self-Reflection</h3>
  <p><strong>Knowledge Areas. </strong>MCH leaders will demonstrate a working knowledge of:</p>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-user"></i> <strong>2K1.</strong> Impact of self-assessment/reflection on leadership style.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>From the literature, we find that &ldquo;self-assessment can increase the interest and motivation level of students for the subjects leading to enhanced learning and better… performance, helping them in development of critical skills for analysis of their own work.&rdquo;<sup>1</sup></p>
    <p>Self-assessment is considered to be a major component of learning in public health.<sup>2</sup> It provides an opportunity for health professionals to reflect on competency-based strengths and weaknesses in order to identify learning needs and reinforce new skills or behaviors in order to improve performance.&nbsp;</p>
    <p>Self-assessment is a prerequisite for maintaining professional competence,<sup>3</sup> and the literature reveals an increasing need for self-assessment in health care settings as health systems change.<sup>4</sup> </p>
    <p>Based on interviews and focus groups with persons who engaged in self-assessment, four types of benefits associated with self-assessment have also been identified in the literature: (1) Learning from experience, (2) Functioning more effectively, (3) Strengthening commitment to competent performance, and (4) Fostering self-agency and authority.<sup>5</sup></p>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-compass3"></i> <strong>2K2.</strong> Characteristics of leadership styles.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Research conducted on leadership finds that a project manager's leadership style influences project success. In addition, different leadership styles are appropriate for different types of projects. For example, on projects of low to medium complexity, emotional resilience and communication have been shown to be the most highly needed styles of leaders. On projects of high complexity, sensitivity is found to be a critical leadership style. The skill sets for these types of leaders are associated more with transformational leadership than transactional leadership.<sup>6</sup></p>
    <p>Leadership styles differ by numerous personal and background factors. For example, some leaders report stronger skills with mentoring/coaching and communication-focused leadership.<sup>7</sup> The research further indicates that the most effective leaders do not rely on only one leadership style; they use many styles continually depending on the workplace situation. There are different ways to categorize leadership styles. Below is one set identified by the business sector (see section below for other styles):<sup>8</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Coercive:</strong> Leaders are defined by the desire to gain immediate compliance. </li>
      <li><strong>Authoritative:</strong> Leaders use their skills to mobilize people toward a vision. </li>
      <li><strong>Affiliative:</strong> Leaders create personal connections, emotional bonds, and harmony. </li>
      <li><strong>Democratic:</strong> Leaders build consensus through active participation and collaboration. </li>
      <li><strong>Pacesetting:</strong> Leaders expect others on the team to be self-directed and internally motivated.</li>
      <li><strong>Coaching:</strong> Leaders use their mentoring skill sets to develop people&rsquo;s strengths for the future.  </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-life-ring"></i> <strong>2K3. </strong>Sources of reward vs. signs of stress/fatigue.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>In MCH, we all work hard, racing against deadlines, fitting projects in under budget and meeting deadlines, attending meetings, and juggling many competing demands. This can lead to increasing levels of stress and eventually burnout. The workforce needs resilience to combat the real threats of stress and burnout. Improving resilience is important because employees identify work as the number-one stressor in their lives.<sup>9</sup></p>
    <p dir="ltr" id="docs-internal-guid-745b592d-7fff-be63-e654-0b0ce1ebf97f">According to the American Psychiatric Association Foundation, "resilience exists when a person can bounce back and thrive from major challenges. It is often tested when stress factors arise in everyday life and when trauma or tragedy strike. Stress is not the only factor that can test a person's resilience; however, how a person handles stress is a strong indicator of their ability to bounce back."<sup>10</sup></p>
    <p>Resilience is more than just coping with stress. Effective, resilient people are also flexible, adapt to new and different situations, are self-directed learners (often learning from their mistakes), ask for help when needed, and use tools like the ones below to combat stress and allow themselves to focus on what matters.<sup>11</sup></p>
  </div>


  <p><strong>Skills</strong></p>
  <p><strong><em>Foundational. </em></strong><em>At a foundational level, MCH leaders will be able to:</em></p>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-traffic-cone"></i> <strong>2S1. </strong>Recognize attitudes/beliefs influencing leadership.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>A person&rsquo;s values reflect their attitudes, beliefs, and experiences.<sup>12</sup> In turn, leadership style reflects personal values.<sup>13</sup></p>
    <p>Values provide guidelines for making decisions, solving problems, and resolving conflicts. They can influence a person&rsquo;s perception of a situation, how they interpret information, and the choices they make.<sup>13</sup></p>
    <p>Honesty, integrity, concern for others, and fairness,  are considered the basis of ethical leadership, with honesty named as the characteristic most admired in a leader.<sup>13</sup></p>
    <p>A leader&rsquo;s values affect their decision-making at the personal and organizational levels.<sup>13</sup></p>
  </div>
 



  <p><em><strong>Advanced.</strong> Building on the foundational skills, MCH leaders will be able to:</em></p>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-light-bulb"></i> <strong>2S2. </strong>Self-reflect to improve programs and outcomes.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>There are many approaches to self-reflection that have been developed for different fields. Here is one technique:<sup>14</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Think about the situation in detail: Ask questions such as what, where, and who was involved?</li>
      <li>Consider how it made you feel and what you were thinking.</li>
      <li>Think about why things happened as they did. How did the situation, yourself, and others interact at the time? Did the situation go well or was there room for improvement?</li>
      <li>Consider how you could have managed the situation differently. Is there anything you could have tried that may have improved the situation? Is there anything you did that was particularly important in the situation?</li>
      <li>Draw on everything you have thought through and use this to learn, change your own practice, and improve. Consider what you will do differently in the future and whether you've learned anything that could apply in other situations.</li>
      <li>Test your reflections. In comparable situations, do things change as you expect them to? This is a chance to repeat the reflective cycle to refine and develop your understanding.</li>
    </ul>
    </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-pin"></i> <strong>2S3. </strong>Identify a framework for feedback.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>To start creating a framework for gathering feedback:<sup>15</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Decide what you'd like to receive feedback on.</li>
      <li>Identify the right peers or mentors to ask for feedback.</li>
      <li>Determine the method by which you'll request feedback: e-mail, surveys, project management software and direct conversation are all possibilities.</li>
      <li>Create appropriate questions. A few examples are:<sup>16</sup>
        <ul>
          <li>How could I have supported you better on this task?</li>
          <li>Have I given you enough information and guidance?</li>
          <li>Is there anything more I can/could have done when you were working on this?</li>
          <li>What would you like me to do differently next time?</li>
          <li>Were you happy with the level of autonomy/responsibility you were given?</li>
          <li>Could I have provided you with more feedback along the way?</li>
          <li>Have you been able to develop your skills while doing this work – how could we have better supported you to develop your skills</li>
          </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Prepare to receive feedback that is both positive and negative.</li>
      <li>Use the feedback you receive to reflect and improve.</li>
    </ul>
    </div>
    
<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-podium"></i> <strong>2S4. </strong>Apply leadership style to promote team function.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Understanding your leadership style will affect who you select as members of your team. While no one leadership style is better than the others, circumstances will make some styles more likely to help a team function well.<sup>17</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Those who tend toward an<strong> authoritarian leadership style</strong>, making most of the decisions and expecting team members to carry out directives, will find that people who like to be guided and supervised in their work will flourish. Those who prefer to make their own decisions will likely resist this leadership style.</li>
      <li><strong>Democratic leaders</strong> like to involve employees in decision-making and approach leadership with a coaching mentality. Team members who are highly skilled and experienced generally work well under this leadership style. However, it requires a significant amount of time from the team leader.</li>
      <li><strong>Laissez-faire leaders</strong> take a hands-off approach to leadership, leaving all decisions to team members and allowing the team to collectively choose its direction. Teams composed of individuals who are highly skilled specialists can be successful under this type of leadership, since team members are free to fully exercise their expertise. However, without clear guidance from a leader, those who are less self-directed and confident can flounder.</li>
      <li>Those with a <strong>transformational leadership style</strong> encourage team members to find and make changes to grow, adapt, and improve their performance. Team members who enjoy being challenged will respond well to this style; those who do not respond well to change will not.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>    
  
